	<section xml:id="the-binomial-distribution" class="unnumbered">
		<title>The Binomial Distribution</title>

<!-- div attr= class="defn"-->
		<p>
			A <term>binomial experiment</term> is a probability experiment possessing the following characteristics:
		</p>

		<p><ol>
			<li>
					<p>
			It has a fixed number of trials, <m>n</m>.
		</p>
			</li>

			<li>
					<p>
			Each trial has only two possible outcomes: success or failure.
		</p>
			</li>

			<li>
					<p>
			The probability of success, <m>p</m>, and the probability of failure, <m>q</m>, are constant.
		</p>
			</li>

			<li>
					<p>
			Each trial is independent of the other trials.
		</p>
			</li>

		</ol></p><!--</div attr= class="defn">-->

<!-- div attr= class="statement"-->
		<p>
			The outcomes of a binomial experiment and the corresponding probabilities of these outcomes are called a <term>binomial distribution</term>.
		</p>

		<p>
			The probability of exactly <m>X</m> successes in <m>n</m> trials with probability of success, <m>p</m>, is <me>P(X) = \frac{n!}{X!(n-X)!}p^X(1-p)^{n-X}\text{  for } X=0,1,2,...,n</me>
		</p><!--</div attr= class="statement">-->

		<p>
			
		</p>

<!-- div attr= class="statement"-->
		<p>
			Good news! The mean and standard deviation of a binomial distribution are simple computations: <me>\mu = ~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~\text{ and } \sigma=~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~</me>
		</p>

		<p>
			As the number of trials in a binomial experiment increases, calculating the probabilities required using the complex formula becomes tedious. Therefore, we will learn how to compute probabilities using tables and using Excel formulas.
		</p>

